name: Owain Thomas
gov_rep_agency: Swedish Board of Health and Welfare (Socialstyrelsen)
nurse_gov_agency: Swedish Board of Health and Welfare (Socialstyrelsen), but we had to adjust the numbers because the available statistics group together ICU nurses and nurse anesthetists (12599 in total), which we did proportionally according to the membership of the Swedish Society of nurse anesthetists and ICU nurses, ANIVA.
nurse_gov: Helen Berthelson, chairman, ANIVA Swedish Society of Anesthetic and ICU nurses.
nurse_gov_excuse: I have contacted the government but they said they did not have the requested data
crit_other: Intensive Care is included in the 5yr anaesthesia and intensive care programme. There is also non-mandatory 2 yr Scandinavian Programme organised by the SSAI, that colleagues specialising in intensive care medicine can attend. There are also 196 (of which 97, 49%) active neonatologists in Sweden who are all paediatricians. A very small number of non-anesthesiologists work at cardiology and neurointensive units. These physicians are not specialists in ICU.
sharemore: This is my second submission - in the first the number of newly trained anesthetic nurses per year was wrong by an order of 10 (an extra 0 - sorry). Not all the data you ask for is available in government databases, unfortunately. I have written '0' where no data is available since a number was required. NB: there were no fields where the actual reply was 0! Data for year 2018 - 2020 we would need to submit a research request to the Swedish board of Health and Welfare's registry (hosp@socialstyrelsen.se) which costs around 1300EUR. The data for active anesthesiologists is obtained from the public data portal at the Board of Health and Welfare (https://sdb.socialstyrelsen.se/if_per/val.aspx) , whose data concerns ACTIVE (ie active, not just registered) anesthesiologists and anesthetic nurses/ICU nurses and is sourced from the Swedish central authority for statistics (www.scb.se). However, the official data for anesthetic / ICU nurses is pooled and we have therefore estimated the number of anesthetic / ICU nurses from the proportional membership in the Swedish Society of Anesthetic and ICU nurses (www.aniva.se). There is no official data on how many non-specialist nurses give sedation for interventions such as gastroscopy, colonoscopy etc. and we have no way of estimating this, although we think that it is uncommon outside university departments in close proximity to an anesthesia service. The data concerning physician trainees since there is no registry including these individuals before they apply for a specialist license. All specialists in anesthesia are also specialists in intensive Care in Sweden. Data on trainee anesthetic nurses is estimated from ANIVA's knowledge of number of places on training programs, which are run by universities. Data concerning number of anesthesia specialist trainees was obtained from SFAI's committee for specialist training.

sharemore: In anesthesia and intensive care departments in Slovenia can employed              only graduate and registered nurses.  1.	A newly-employed nurse should circulate in all branches of anesthesiology which lasts for one year and 6 months in intensive care. The circulation is led by a Anesthetic Educational Nurse. She or he prepares an individual program of training and circulating. The training consist of theoretical and practical part and examination. Practical training is conducted by experienced anesthetic, educational and head nurses. Each probation ends with a colloquium. When the candidate passes the colloquia in all areas of anesthesia, and receives a positive assessment from all mentors and after 6 months of intensive therapy he can work independently in all field of anesthesia.  2.	Intensive care nurse works under mentor control for 3 months. Additional 3 months can take care for patient independent but still under mentor control. After that time she or he can work independent.
